  "prompt": "I'm 17 year old. How do I know if I have breast cancer?",
  "response": "At 17, breast cancer is extremely rare. However, it's important to be aware of your body and know what's normal for you. Here are some steps:\n\n1. Self-examination:\n- Check for unusual lumps or changes in breast tissue\n- Look for skin changes, dimpling, or unusual discharge\n- Perform monthly self-exams\n\n2. Warning signs:\n- Unexplained lumps\n- Changes in breast size or shape\n- Skin changes\n- Nipple discharge\n- Persistent pain\n\n3. Risk factors:\n- Family history of breast cancer\n- Genetic predispositions\n- Rare in teenagers, but not impossible\n\n4. Recommendations:\n- Speak with your parents or guardian\n- Schedule an appointment with a healthcare professional\n- If concerned, see a doctor for proper examination\n- Regular check-ups are important\n\n5. Remember:\n- Most breast changes are not cancer\n- Most lumps are benign (non-cancerous)\n- Professional medical advice is crucial\n\nImportant: Only a medical professional can provide a definitive diagnosis. If you're concerned, talk to your parents or a healthcare provider who can guide you properly.",
